<h1 id="Wells" class="page-header">
    <h1>Making an Omelette! (My Way)...</h1>
    <h4>by Talia LeRay</h4></h1>

<p class="lead"></p>
<p>I make this omelette when I am at my house in Brooklyn, typically on a Saturday morning.</p>

<h3>Ingredients</h3>
<div class="panel panel-success">
  <div class="panel-body">
        Here are the ingredients I use to make an omelette:
            <ul>
                <li class="odd">2 eggs</li>
                <li class="even">Lawry's seasoning salt</li> 
                <li class="odd">Fresh garlic pegs</li>
                <li class="even">Spinach</li> 
                <li class="odd">Tomato</li>
                <li class="even">Bacon or Sausage</li>
                <li class="odd">Pepppers (green, red, yellow)</li>
                <li class="even">Onions</li>
                <li class="odd">Avacado (on the side)</li>
                <li class="even">4 cheese mix</li>
            </ul>
  </div>
    
</div>
<div class="panel panel-info">
  <div class="panel-heading">Directions</div>
  <div class="panel-body">
    <ol>
                <li class="odd">Crack both eggs in a bowl and mix it until scrambled.</li>
                <br>
                
                <li class="even">Make a choice of the meat you want (sausage, bacon or both!) and allow the meat(s) to cook in a pan.</li>
                <br>
                
                <li class="odd">Chop up the garlic, spinach, tomato, onion, peppers and the peppers while the meat is cooking. Check on the meat as you're chopping up the ingredients.</li>
                <br>
                
                <li class="even">Add the chopped ingredients and the cooked meat to the bowl with the scrambled eggs. Base the bottom of a pan and add the mix to the pan</li>
                <br>
                
                <li class="odd">Allow the omelette to cook on one side for 4 minutes on a medium to low fire and turn over when done. Add cheese (if you want) to the omlette and close it</li>
                <br>
                
                <li class="even">ENJOY!</li>
            </ol>
  </div>
</div>
